    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="470"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d470">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.7111/51.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Page</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 21, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>152. Sir E. Grey informs me that a negro named Sam has been spreading propaganda
                    among the population of Boggs, Oklahoma, and selling shares in an “African
                    Trading Company” with a view to inducing negroes to emigrate to the Gold Coast
                    Colony. The British Government has convincing information that Sam’s
                    transactions are not genuine nor the company for which he acts reliable and the
                    Gold Coast Government have denied that they have any authorized <pb facs="0438"
                        n="322" xml:id="pg_322"/> immigration agent. The British Ambassador at
                    Washington reports that five hundred negro emigrants purpose to leave the United
                    States for the Gold Coast about the 26th instant on the representations of Sam,
                    and Sir Edward Grey earnestly requests that you will do all in your power to
                    prevent the departure of these emigrants since he is morally certain that the
                    entire scheme is fraudulent and that the intending emigrants are foredoomed to
                    disappointment.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
